title: Title
Synopsis
table-0271-616.caption: Segments
data: Memorable clips from the shows past.
Same as the Around the Net segment, except that after the five videos, more adult content is shown in uncensored form. Airs on the early morning repeats only.
The show cast goes around the blogosphere to find blogs that deal with very specific things.
AOTS! shows viewers things they should be downloading on their computer. Hosted by Sarah Lane. "Gems of the Internet" which found oddities on the internet.
The hosts single out one online video in particular that has poor content, a contrived setting, or people who are clearly trying too hard.
The hosts promote free stuff for any lucky viewer and the next day the winner announced prior to the next giveaway.
Weird and wacky oddities found on the internet.
The hosts give tips on how to hack or alter everyday gadgets, etc.

A segment where gambling expert Jimmy the Geek gives out picks for smart betting on upcoming sporting events. Predictions are based on video game simulations, basic knowledge on the sport, history, statistics etc. Jimmy emulates a slimy individual often saying funny yet mildly sexual & obscene comments as metaphors to bets.
Weston Scott shows different military or combat defense techniques.
A daily forum hosted by Kevin Pereira featuring different opinions on the latest tech related news usually with one to three guests appearing live via satellite.
The Lush (also called The Lush for the Drunk)
The latest in military weaponry narrated by Pereira.
Olivia Munn shares her favorite magazine articles.
The show cast (typically Pereira) discuss new and/or experimental cars.
A random segment which highlights the advancement of robotics and their imminent takeover of the world.
The latest in sneaker culture which includes the newest shoes to hit the market, blogs/websites on shoes, etc. Narrated by Pereira.
Contest where fans and viewers of the show submit videos of a specific topic (80s video game commercials, Horror films, Holiday specials, etc.) in exchange for prizes.

Viewers send in videos of themselves, asking questions, giving opinions, etc. Munn and Pereira originally introduced it by saying something along the lines of "Let's talk to you guys over in the army of monitor heads" until the army of monitor heads were retired in mid 2008.
Pereira and Munn talk with viewers via webcams about various topics.
"WebTools" takes a look at the web-based applications that enrich online life and where to find them.
What's Up with Japan? (also called What's Up with the World?)

Pereira talks about the strange occurrences within Japan, from tech to popular culture. In relating to Japan, the segment's title is also given in Japanese as 現代日本事情 (Gendai Nippon Jijō), a rough translation of the English title.

data: (Pan Hla 2004: 25–26) says per Mon records King Wareru proclaimed independence on Thursday, 6th waning of Old Tagu 648 ME (4 April 1287), which is in contradiction with full moon of Tabodwe 649 (19 January 1288) per Burmese records. Pan Hla conjectures the January 1288 date is the date of coronation.

The founding date of Mrauk-U appears differently in different sources. The Burmese encyclopedia (Myanma Swezon Kyan Vol. 9 1964: 425) gives the date as Sunday, 1st waxing of Natdaw 792 (16 November 1430). But (Harvey 1925: 139) gives 1433, and (Sandamala Linkara Vol. 2 1999: 13) gives Sunday, 1st waxing of Tawthalin 792 (20 August 1430).

(Hmannan Vol. 3 2003: 172–173): The Burmese chronicles do not state that King Anaukpetlun officially moved the capital to Pegu. But Anaukpetlun arrived at Pegu in early May 1613 as part of his war operations and hosted the first function at his temporary palace on 14 May 1613 (10th waning of Kason 975). He did not go back to Ava afterwards.

table-0271-961.caption: Historical points
data: While there was some truth to it, on the battle field the wearing of sashes and other identifying insignia were needed because on and off the battle field those from similar classes tended to dress in similar fashions.
Cromwell tells Charles I that the kind of government that he believes England should have is a democracy.
The famous soldiers' prayer: "O Lord, Thou knowest how busy I must be this day. If I forget Thee, do not forget me" is put into Cromwell's mouth.
The infantry wore a trademark red coat – the origins of the red coats worn by British infantry in subsequent centuries.
Cromwell is named commander-in-chief of the Parliamentary forces, while Sir Thomas Fairfax is shown as Cromwell's subordinate.
Cromwell is shown bringing troops into the House of Commons and declaring that he now has a majority.

Charles is depicted as planning a second Civil War after his defeat, but the plot is discovered before it can begin. Charles is brought to trial merely for planning this strategy, not for carrying it out.
He, however, was not knighted until during the Civil War and not elevated to the peerage until 1661.
Sir Edward Hyde gives damning testimony against Charles at the king's trial.
Hyde turned against the king, but did not actively testify at the trial.
By the time Cromwell was actually offered the crown—towards the end of his life in 1657—Ireton, his son-in-law, had been dead for nearly six years.
Cromwell dismisses the idea of becoming king instantly, laughing it off as absurd after what he fought for.

Cromwell was immediately reluctant to accept the office of king, but took the offer very seriously as so many in Parliament thought it vital. He turned the offer down after several weeks of negotiations, mainly because the army was opposed to it.
In truth, they had four years and this scene takes place after Cromwell is offered the crown, which in reality happened eight years after Charles' execution.
The statement he actually made was 'Take away that fool's bauble, the mace'.
In the film, Rump Parliament's dismissal is portrayed after Cromwell is granted the crown.
